\nSchoeneck is part of the [[Cocalico School District]].  A long time presence in Schoeneck, the Schoeneck Elementary School closed in June 2011. Schoeneck students will be transported to the [[Denver]] Elementary School for future school years.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Evans|first1=Dean|title=Cocalico School District OKs Schoeneck Elementary closure|url=http://lancasteronline.com/news/cocalico-school-district-oks-schoeneck-elementary-closure/article_5027d89b-0df4-5fb4-b0d8-1be45d3a266a.html|website=Lancaster Online|accessdate=2 August 2017}}</ref>  Schoeneck is also home to the Schoeneck Volunteer Fire Company. [[File:Schoeneck1-9-1.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Schoeneck Engine 1-9-1.|Engine 1-9-1 ''Schoeneck, Pennsylvania''.]] [[File:Schoeneck1-9-2.jpg|thumb|center|alt=Schoeneck Engine 1-9-1.|Engine 1-9-2 ''Schoeneck, Pennsylvania''.]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070817005606/http://www.cocalico.k12.pa.us/elem/schoe/index.html Schoeneck Elementary School]\n\n{{Lancaster County, Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schoeneck,_Pennsylvania"}
{"title_page": "Samira Ahmed", "text_new": "{{Update|date=December 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Samira Ahmed\n| image = Week of Women (31015246296).jpg\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption = Ahmed in 2016\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1968|6|15}}\n| birth_place = London,{{cn|date=December 2019}} England\n| residence = London, England\n| citizenship =\n| education =\n| alma_mater = [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]<br />[[City, University of London|City University, London]]\n| occupation = [[News Presenter]] Journalism\n| website = http://www.samiraahmed.co.uk/\n}}\n{{hatnote|Not to be confused with the American author [[Samira Ahmed (author)|of the same name]]}}\n'''Samira Ahmed''' (born 15 June 1968)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0014174/ \"Samira Ahmed, IMDB\"]</ref>  is a British journalist, writer and broadcaster at the [[BBC]], where she has presented [[BBC Radio 3|Radio 3's]] ''[[Night Waves]]'' and [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4's]] ''[[PM (BBC Radio 4)|PM]]'', ''[[The World Tonight]]'', ''[[Sunday (radio programme)|Sunday]]'' and ''[[Front Row (radio programme)|Front Row]]'' and has presented the [[The Proms|Proms]] for [[BBC Four]].<ref name=\"BBCN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/3k4cHYTXDCScnTnpN6hrzYp/samira-ahmed|title=Samira Ahmed|work=BBC Newswatch|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nHer writing has appeared in ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'' and for ''[[The Spectator]]'' magazine's Arts Blog. She was a reporter and presenter on ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' from 2000 to 2011. She presented ''[[Sunday Morning Live (BBC)|Sunday Morning Live]]'', a topical discussion programme on [[BBC One]] from 2012 to 2013.\n\n==Early life==\nAhmed was born in Wandsworth<ref>[https://www.findmypast.co.uk/transcript?id=BMD%2FB%2F1968%2F3%2FAZ%2F000011%2F045 \"Birth record\"]</ref> to Athar<ref name=\"WhosWho\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-246169 |title=Ahmed, Samira|publisher=[[Who's_Who_(UK)]] |accessdate=2 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Lalita (n\u00e9e Chatterjee, born 1939, [[Lucknow]])<ref name=IMDb>{{cite web|title=Lalita Ahmed|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0014161|publisher=IMDb}}</ref> Ahmed. Her mother is a TV presenter, actor, chef and writer on Indian cookery<ref>{{cite web |title=Celebrity Masterchef: Its part in my downfall |url=http://www.samiraahmed.co.uk/celebrity-masterchef-its-part-in-my-downfall/ |website=Samira Ahmed: Journalist, Writer, Broadcaster |accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> who previously worked for the Hindi service of the [[BBC World Service]] in [[Bush House]] as well as [[All India Radio]] in India.<ref name=\"Ahmed\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/samira-ahmed-my-life-in-media-461401.html|title=Samira Ahmed: My Life in Media|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=13 August 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522223116/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/samira-ahmed-my-life-in-media-461401.html|archivedate=22 May 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She attended [[Wimbledon High School]], an independent day school for girls, and edited the school magazine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wimbledon High |url=https://www.tatler.com/school/wimbledon-high-tatler-school-guide |website=[[Tatler]] Schools Guide 2020 |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]] |date=21 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Doing the groundwork |journal=Verve \u2013 the annual magazine for the [[GDST]] Alumnae Network |date=7 February 2017 |issue=16/17 |pages=10\u201311 |url=https://issuu.com/gdst/docs/verve-magazine-gdst-alumnae-network |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAhmed read English at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]], which made her an honorary fellow in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Five Honorary Fellows Sworn in at St Edmund Hall |url=https://www.seh.ox.ac.uk/news/5-honorary-fellows |publisher=St Edmund Hall, Oxford |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> While an undergraduate she edited ''[[The Isis Magazine|Isis]]'' and the ''Union'' magazines, both Oxford University student publications,<ref name=\"SAbio\">[http://www.samiraahmed.co.uk/?page_id=2 About] Samira Ahmed.</ref> and won the [[Harrods bombings#Memorials|Philip Geddes Journalism Prize]] for her work on student newspapers.<ref>[http://www.geddesprize.co.uk/Past_Winners.htm Past Lecturers] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120804033617/http://www.geddesprize.co.uk/Past_Winners.htm |date=4 August 2012 }} Philip Geddes Memorial Fund.</ref> After graduation she completed a Postgraduate Diploma in Newspaper Journalism at [[City, University of London|City University, London]].<ref name=\"Malik\">Rabiah Malik, [http://www.clickandquill.org/2011/02/23/samira-ahmed-2/ Samira Ahmed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611072707/http://www.clickandquill.org/2011/02/23/samira-ahmed-2/ |date=11 June 2011 }}, Chick and Quill, City University alumni website, 23 February 2011.</ref> She recalls that [[Lucy Mathen]], the first female Asian reporter on BBC television,<ref>Samira Ahmed, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/sep/29/newsround-playground-racism-letter \"Newsround, racism and me\"], ''The Guardian'', 29 September 2011.</ref> who worked on ''[[Newsround|John Craven's Newsround]]'', was an inspirational figure for her, as was broadcaster Shyama Perera,<ref name=\"Malik\"/> who was working in [[Fleet Street]] at around the same time.<ref>Shyama Perera, [https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/shyama-perera-how-i-have-come-to-love-the-flag-480976.html \"How I have come to love the flag\"], ''The Independent'', 4 June 2006.</ref>\n\n==Journalism career==\n[[File:London Thinks- A Scientist, an Atheist Biblical Scholar and a Vicar Walk into an Ethical Society.webm|thumb|Ahmed talks with [[Francesca Stavrakopoulou]], [[Giles Fraser]] and [[Adam Rutherford]] at [[Conway Hall]].]]\nAhmed became a BBC news trainee in 1990. After two years on attachments, she began to work as a network radio reporter in 1992 on such programmes as ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]''. Fearful her short BBC contract would not be renewed after a mishap in a difficult situation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Ahmed|first=Samira|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/my-greatest-mistake-samira-ahmed-presenter-channel-4-news-80907.html|title=My Greatest Mistake: Samira Ahmed, presenter, Channel 4 News|work=The Independent|date=3 December 2003|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> Ahmed applied for, and was taken on, by [[BBC World]] for work as a presenter, which led to her becoming a reporter for ''[[Newsnight]]''.<ref name=\"BBCN\" /><ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Rob|last2=Ahmed|first2=Samira|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/mar/14/broadcasting.mondaymediasection|title=How to be... Samira Ahmed|work=The Guardian|date=14 March 2005|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> She was the BBC's Los Angeles correspondent during 1996\u201397 and filed reports on the [[O. J. Simpson murder case|O. J. Simpson civil trial]].<ref name=\"BBCN\" /><ref name=\"MEvenN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/samira-ahmed-biography-1008539|title=Samira Ahmed Biography|work=Manchester Evening News|date=12 January 2013|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> Ahmed briefly worked for [[Deutsche Welle]] in Berlin as an anchor and political correspondent, but then returned for a brief spell with BBC World and as a night shift presenter for [[BBC News 24]] before taking maternity leave.<ref name=\"Harris\"/>\n\nAhmed joined ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' in April 2000, and became a presenter in July 2002. In June 2011 Ahmed left Channel 4, and went freelance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jun/06/samira-ahmed-to-leave-channel-4|title=Samira Ahmed to leave Channel 4|work=The Guardian|date=6 June 2011|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 she won Broadcaster of the Year at the annual [[Stonewall Awards]] for her special report on \"corrective\" rape of lesbian women in South Africa.<ref name=sw2009>{{cite web|title=2009 winners|url=http://www.stonewall.org.uk/media/current_releases/3584.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091109032311/http://www.stonewall.org.uk/media/current_releases/3584.asp|url-status=dead|archive-date=2009-11-09|publisher=Stonewall}}</ref> The report was made after [[ActionAid]] contacted her about their campaign against [[homophobic]] crime.<ref name=cm>{{cite web|title=Celebrity Mastermind: memories of the black leather chair|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/celebrity-mastermind-memories-of-the-black-leather-chair|publisher=Channel 4|author=Samira Ahmed|date=30 December 2010}}</ref> She won the BBC's ''[[Celebrity Mastermind]]'', with a specialist round on [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]], the author of the ''[[Little House on the Prairie]]'' books, in December 2010. Again, in 2019 Ahmed won the Celebrity Mastermind Champion of Champions, she wore a [[Space 1999]] costume.<ref name=cm/><ref name=Guardian-mastermind-laura>{{cite news|last1=Ahmed |first1=Samira |title=Spirit of the frontier|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/nov/26/little-house-on-the-prairie-ingalls-wilder|accessdate=24 June 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=26 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nSince October 2011, she has been a regular newspaper reviewer on ''[[Lorraine (TV programme)|Lorraine]]''.<ref name=IMDb /> From June 2012 to November 2013 she presented the third and fourth series of ''[[Sunday Morning Live (BBC)|Sunday Morning Live]]'' on [[BBC One]].<ref name=\"SAbio\"/> In October 2012, Ahmed succeeded [[Raymond Snoddy|Ray Snoddy]] as presenter of ''[[Newswatch (UK TV series)|Newswatch]]'' on the BBC News Channel.<ref>[http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/content/samira-ahmed-takes-over-ray-snoddy-newswatch-presenter \"Samira Ahmed takes over from Ray Snoddy as Newswatch presenter\"], ''Press Gazette'', 3 October 2012.</ref>\n\nShe is a Visiting Professor of Journalism at [[Kingston University]] and a regular contributor to ''[[The Big Issue]]''.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qnbd/features/presenters \"Presenters\"], ''Sunday'', BBC Radio 4.</ref>\n\nIn September 2019 she interviewed [[Margaret Atwood]] about the novelist's new book ''[[The Testaments]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], which was simulcast to more than 1,000 cinemas around the world as part of [[National Theatre Live]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fraser |first1=Garnet |title=Margaret Atwood interview to air live in cinemas to promote Handmaid\u2019s Tale sequel |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2019/03/07/margaret-atwood-interview-to-air-live-in-cinemas-to-promote-handmaids-tale-sequel.html |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=The Toronto Star |publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Ltd. |date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Equal pay tribunal===\n\nAhmed filed legal proceedings against the BBC under the [[Equal Pay Act 1970|Equal Pay Act]] in October 2019.<ref name=\"BBCEqualPay\">{{cite news |title=Samira Ahmed takes BBC to court over equal pay |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50128698 |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=BBC |date=21 October 2019}}</ref> The London Central Employment Tribunal unanimously found in her favour on 10 January 2020.<ref name=\"BBCWon\">{{cite news |title=Samira Ahmed wins BBC equal pay tribunal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50599080?ocid=socialflow_twitter&ns_campaign=bbcnews&ns_source=twitter&ns_mchannel=social |accessdate=10 January 2020 |work=BBC News |date=10 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"JUDGEMENT\">{{cite web |title=Ahmed -v- BBC [pdf] |url=https://www.judiciary.uk/judgments/ahmed-v-bbc/ |website=www.judiciary.uk |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> On 24 February 2020 it was announced that a settlement had been reached with the BBC, but no figure for this was made public.<ref name=\"BBC51611570\">{{cite news |title=Samira Ahmed reaches settlement with BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51611570 |accessdate=24 February 2020 |work=BBC News |date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAhmed is married to Brian Millar.<ref name=\"WhosWho\" /> The couple live in London and have a son and a daughter.<ref name=\"ExpressStyle\">{{cite news |last1=Mulley |first1=Laura |title=News presenter Samira Ahmed: As a woman, you\u2019ll always be judged on what you wear |url=https://www.express.co.uk/life-style/style/612048/News-presenter-Samira-Ahmed-style-fashion-secrets |accessdate=2 August 2019 |work=The Daily Express |date=18 October 2015}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.samiraahmed.co.uk/}}\n*{{IMDb name|0014174}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00qjrk2 Newswatch] (BBC News Channel)\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qsq5 Front Row] (BBC Radio 4)\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/samira-ahmed Ahmed articles from ''The Guardian'']\n*[http://www.spectator.co.uk/search/author/tfad-author/?searchString=Samira%20Ahmed Ahmed articles from ''Spectator'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahmed, Samira}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:BBC World News]]\n[[Category:English people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:ITN newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:British women journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wimbledon High School]]\n", "text_old": "{{Update|date=December 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Samira Ahmed\n| image = Week of Women (31015246296).jpg\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption = Ahmed in 2016\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1968|6|15}}\n| birth_place = London,{{cn|date=December 2019}} England\n| residence = London, England\n| citizenship =\n| education =\n| alma_mater = [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]<br />[[City, University of London|City University, London]]\n| occupation = [[News Presenter]] Journalism\n| website = http://www.samiraahmed.co.uk/\n}}\n{{hatnote|Not to be confused with the American author [[Samira Ahmed (author)|of the same name]]}}\n'''Samira Ahmed''' (born 15 June 1968)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0014174/ \"Samira Ahmed, IMDB\"]</ref>  is a British journalist, writer and broadcaster at the [[BBC]], where she has presented [[BBC Radio 3|Radio 3's]] ''[[Night Waves]]'' and [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4's]] ''[[PM (BBC Radio 4)|PM]]'', ''[[The World Tonight]]'', ''[[Sunday (radio programme)|Sunday]]'' and ''[[Front Row (radio programme)|Front Row]]'' and has presented the [[The Proms|Proms]] for [[BBC Four]].<ref name=\"BBCN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/profiles/3k4cHYTXDCScnTnpN6hrzYp/samira-ahmed|title=Samira Ahmed|work=BBC Newswatch|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nHer writing has appeared in ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'' and for ''[[The Spectator]]'' magazine's Arts Blog. She was a reporter and presenter on ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' from 2000 to 2011. She presented ''[[Sunday Morning Live (BBC)|Sunday Morning Live]]'', a topical discussion programme on [[BBC One]] from 2012 to 2013.\n\n==Early life==\nAhmed was born in Wandsworth<ref>[https://www.findmypast.co.uk/transcript?id=BMD%2FB%2F1968%2F3%2FAZ%2F000011%2F045 \"Birth record\"]</ref> to Athar<ref name=\"WhosWho\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-246169 |title=Ahmed, Samira|publisher=[[Who's_Who_(UK)]] |accessdate=2 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Lalita (n\u00e9e Chatterjee, born 1939, [[Lucknow]])<ref name=IMDb>{{cite web|title=Lalita Ahmed|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0014161|publisher=IMDb}}</ref> Ahmed. Her mother is a TV presenter, chef and writer on Indian cookery<ref>{{cite web |title=Celebrity Masterchef: Its part in my downfall |url=http://www.samiraahmed.co.uk/celebrity-masterchef-its-part-in-my-downfall/ |website=Samira Ahmed: Journalist, Writer, Broadcaster |accessdate=13 September 2019}}</ref> who previously worked for the Hindi service of the [[BBC World Service]] in [[Bush House]].<ref name=\"Ahmed\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/samira-ahmed-my-life-in-media-461401.html|title=Samira Ahmed: My Life in Media|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=13 August 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522223116/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/samira-ahmed-my-life-in-media-461401.html|archivedate=22 May 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She attended [[Wimbledon High School]], an independent day school for girls, and edited the school magazine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wimbledon High |url=https://www.tatler.com/school/wimbledon-high-tatler-school-guide |website=[[Tatler]] Schools Guide 2020 |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]] |date=21 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Doing the groundwork |journal=Verve \u2013 the annual magazine for the [[GDST]] Alumnae Network |date=7 February 2017 |issue=16/17 |pages=10\u201311 |url=https://issuu.com/gdst/docs/verve-magazine-gdst-alumnae-network |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAhmed read English at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]], which made her an honorary fellow in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Five Honorary Fellows Sworn in at St Edmund Hall |url=https://www.seh.ox.ac.uk/news/5-honorary-fellows |publisher=St Edmund Hall, Oxford |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> While an undergraduate she edited ''[[The Isis Magazine|Isis]]'' and the ''Union'' magazines, both Oxford University student publications,<ref name=\"SAbio\">[http://www.samiraahmed.co.uk/?page_id=2 About] Samira Ahmed.</ref> and won the [[Harrods bombings#Memorials|Philip Geddes Journalism Prize]] for her work on student newspapers.<ref>[http://www.geddesprize.co.uk/Past_Winners.htm Past Lecturers] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120804033617/http://www.geddesprize.co.uk/Past_Winners.htm |date=4 August 2012 }} Philip Geddes Memorial Fund.</ref> After graduation she completed a Postgraduate Diploma in Newspaper Journalism at [[City, University of London|City University, London]].<ref name=\"Malik\">Rabiah Malik, [http://www.clickandquill.org/2011/02/23/samira-ahmed-2/ Samira Ahmed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611072707/http://www.clickandquill.org/2011/02/23/samira-ahmed-2/ |date=11 June 2011 }}, Chick and Quill, City University alumni website, 23 February 2011.</ref> She recalls that [[Lucy Mathen]], the first female Asian reporter on BBC television,<ref>Samira Ahmed, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/sep/29/newsround-playground-racism-letter \"Newsround, racism and me\"], ''The Guardian'', 29 September 2011.</ref> who worked on ''[[Newsround|John Craven's Newsround]]'', was an inspirational figure for her, as was broadcaster Shyama Perera,<ref name=\"Malik\"/> who was working in [[Fleet Street]] at around the same time.<ref>Shyama Perera, [https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/shyama-perera-how-i-have-come-to-love-the-flag-480976.html \"How I have come to love the flag\"], ''The Independent'', 4 June 2006.</ref>\n\n==Journalism career==\n[[File:London Thinks- A Scientist, an Atheist Biblical Scholar and a Vicar Walk into an Ethical Society.webm|thumb|Ahmed talks with [[Francesca Stavrakopoulou]], [[Giles Fraser]] and [[Adam Rutherford]] at [[Conway Hall]].]]\nAhmed became a BBC news trainee in 1990. After two years on attachments, she began to work as a network radio reporter in 1992 on such programmes as ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]''. Fearful her short BBC contract would not be renewed after a mishap in a difficult situation,<ref>{{cite news|last=Ahmed|first=Samira|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/my-greatest-mistake-samira-ahmed-presenter-channel-4-news-80907.html|title=My Greatest Mistake: Samira Ahmed, presenter, Channel 4 News|work=The Independent|date=3 December 2003|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> Ahmed applied for, and was taken on, by [[BBC World]] for work as a presenter, which led to her becoming a reporter for ''[[Newsnight]]''.<ref name=\"BBCN\" /><ref name=\"Harris\">{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Rob|last2=Ahmed|first2=Samira|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2005/mar/14/broadcasting.mondaymediasection|title=How to be... Samira Ahmed|work=The Guardian|date=14 March 2005|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> She was the BBC's Los Angeles correspondent during 1996\u201397 and filed reports on the [[O. J. Simpson murder case|O. J. Simpson civil trial]].<ref name=\"BBCN\" /><ref name=\"MEvenN\">{{cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/samira-ahmed-biography-1008539|title=Samira Ahmed Biography|work=Manchester Evening News|date=12 January 2013|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref> Ahmed briefly worked for [[Deutsche Welle]] in Berlin as an anchor and political correspondent, but then returned for a brief spell with BBC World and as a night shift presenter for [[BBC News 24]] before taking maternity leave.<ref name=\"Harris\"/>\n\nAhmed joined ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' in April 2000, and became a presenter in July 2002. In June 2011 Ahmed left Channel 4, and went freelance.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sweney|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jun/06/samira-ahmed-to-leave-channel-4|title=Samira Ahmed to leave Channel 4|work=The Guardian|date=6 June 2011|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 she won Broadcaster of the Year at the annual [[Stonewall Awards]] for her special report on \"corrective\" rape of lesbian women in South Africa.<ref name=sw2009>{{cite web|title=2009 winners|url=http://www.stonewall.org.uk/media/current_releases/3584.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091109032311/http://www.stonewall.org.uk/media/current_releases/3584.asp|url-status=dead|archive-date=2009-11-09|publisher=Stonewall}}</ref> The report was made after [[ActionAid]] contacted her about their campaign against [[homophobic]] crime.<ref name=cm>{{cite web|title=Celebrity Mastermind: memories of the black leather chair|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/celebrity-mastermind-memories-of-the-black-leather-chair|publisher=Channel 4|author=Samira Ahmed|date=30 December 2010}}</ref> She won the BBC's ''[[Celebrity Mastermind]]'', with a specialist round on [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]], the author of the ''[[Little House on the Prairie]]'' books, in December 2010. Again, in 2019 Ahmed won the Celebrity Mastermind Champion of Champions, she wore a [[Space 1999]] costume.<ref name=cm/><ref name=Guardian-mastermind-laura>{{cite news|last1=Ahmed |first1=Samira |title=Spirit of the frontier|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/nov/26/little-house-on-the-prairie-ingalls-wilder|accessdate=24 June 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=26 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nSince October 2011, she has been a regular newspaper reviewer on ''[[Lorraine (TV programme)|Lorraine]]''.<ref name=IMDb /> From June 2012 to November 2013 she presented the third and fourth series of ''[[Sunday Morning Live (BBC)|Sunday Morning Live]]'' on [[BBC One]].<ref name=\"SAbio\"/> In October 2012, Ahmed succeeded [[Raymond Snoddy|Ray Snoddy]] as presenter of ''[[Newswatch (UK TV series)|Newswatch]]'' on the BBC News Channel.<ref>[http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/content/samira-ahmed-takes-over-ray-snoddy-newswatch-presenter \"Samira Ahmed takes over from Ray Snoddy as Newswatch presenter\"], ''Press Gazette'', 3 October 2012.</ref>\n\nShe is a Visiting Professor of Journalism at [[Kingston University]] and a regular contributor to ''[[The Big Issue]]''.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qnbd/features/presenters \"Presenters\"], ''Sunday'', BBC Radio 4.</ref>\n\nIn September 2019 she interviewed [[Margaret Atwood]] about the novelist's new book ''[[The Testaments]]'' at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]], which was simulcast to more than 1,000 cinemas around the world as part of [[National Theatre Live]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fraser |first1=Garnet |title=Margaret Atwood interview to air live in cinemas to promote Handmaid\u2019s Tale sequel |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2019/03/07/margaret-atwood-interview-to-air-live-in-cinemas-to-promote-handmaids-tale-sequel.html |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=The Toronto Star |publisher=Toronto Star Newspapers Ltd. |date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Equal pay tribunal===\n\nAhmed filed legal proceedings against the BBC under the [[Equal Pay Act 1970|Equal Pay Act]] in October 2019.<ref name=\"BBCEqualPay\">{{cite news |title=Samira Ahmed takes BBC to court over equal pay |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50128698 |accessdate=21 October 2019 |work=BBC |date=21 October 2019}}</ref> The London Central Employment Tribunal unanimously found in her favour on 10 January 2020.<ref name=\"BBCWon\">{{cite news |title=Samira Ahmed wins BBC equal pay tribunal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-50599080?ocid=socialflow_twitter&ns_campaign=bbcnews&ns_source=twitter&ns_mchannel=social |accessdate=10 January 2020 |work=BBC News |date=10 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"JUDGEMENT\">{{cite web |title=Ahmed -v- BBC [pdf] |url=https://www.judiciary.uk/judgments/ahmed-v-bbc/ |website=www.judiciary.uk |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> On 24 February 2020 it was announced that a settlement had been reached with the BBC, but no figure for this was made public.<ref name=\"BBC51611570\">{{cite news |title=Samira Ahmed reaches settlement with BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51611570 |accessdate=24 February 2020 |work=BBC News |date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAhmed is married to Brian Millar.<ref name=\"WhosWho\" /> The couple live in London and have a son and a daughter.<ref name=\"ExpressStyle\">{{cite news |last1=Mulley |first1=Laura |title=News presenter Samira Ahmed: As a woman, you\u2019ll always be judged on what you wear |url=https://www.express.co.uk/life-style/style/612048/News-presenter-Samira-Ahmed-style-fashion-secrets |accessdate=2 August 2019 |work=The Daily Express |date=18 October 2015}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.samiraahmed.co.uk/}}\n*{{IMDb name|0014174}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00qjrk2 Newswatch] (BBC News Channel)\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qsq5 Front Row] (BBC Radio 4)\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/samira-ahmed Ahmed articles from ''The Guardian'']\n*[http://www.spectator.co.uk/search/author/tfad-author/?searchString=Samira%20Ahmed Ahmed articles from ''Spectator'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahmed, Samira}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of City, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:BBC World News]]\n[[Category:English people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:ITN newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:British women journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Wimbledon High School]]\n", "name_user": "Chirags", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Updated early life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samira_Ahmed"}
{"title_page": "Ronks, Pennsylvania", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Ronks\n|official_name            = \n|settlement_type          = [[census-designated place]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Red Caboose Motel Ronks Pennsylvania 1.jpg\n|imagesize                = 325px\n|image_caption            = The Red Caboose Motel in Ronks consists of decommissioned railroad cabooses (2014)\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA Pennsylvania\n|pushpin_label_position   = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location within the U.S. state of Pennsylvania\n|pushpin_mapsize          = \n|image_map                = \n|map_caption              = Location within Lancaster county\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Pennsylvania]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Pennsylvania|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania|Lancaster]]\n\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = <!-- Mayor -->\n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           =\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[United States Census, 2010|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 362\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|coordinates              = {{coord|40|01|34|N|76|10|07|W|type:city_region:US-PA|display=inline,title}}\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 17572\n|area_code                = [[Area code 717|717]] Exchange: 687\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = \n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              =  1185421<ref>{{gnis|1185421}}</ref>\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n}}\n'''Ronks''' is a small farming community and [[census-designated place]] in [[Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]], just west of [[Paradise, Pennsylvania]]. The town is noted for being the home of Ronks Concrete Company. The community is home to several [[Amish]] themed tourist attractions, shops, restaurants, and lodging lining the [[U.S. Route 30 in Pennsylvania|Lincoln Highway]]. It is also close to the [[Strasburg Rail Road]] and the [[Railroad Museum of Pennsylvania]].  The community has a large Amish and [[Mennonite]] population.  As of the 2010 census the population was 362 residents.\n\n<gallery mode=packed heights=200>\nRonks Pennsylvania Post Office - panoramio.jpg|Post office\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons category-inline|Ronks, Pennsylvania}}\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n{{Lancaster County, Pennsylvania|state=collapsed}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Lancaster County, Pennsylvania]]\n\n\n{{LancasterCountyPA-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                     = Ronks\n|official_name            = \n|settlement_type          = [[census-designated place]]\n|nickname                 = \n